                </div>
                <p>The core of the<span class="font-weight-700"> Mavrick 440 </span>is the 440 cc<span class="font-weight-700"> oil-cooled, single-cylinder engine</span> developed through the Hero-Harley partnership. While the architecture will remain the same, the 2025 update is highly anticipated to bring crucial performance tuning changes to better compete with segment rivals known for high power figures.</p>
                <p><span class="font-weight-700">The Revamped 440cc Engine Tuning</span></p>
                <p>The current engine delivers its performance low down, which is excellent for city riding. For 2025, Hero is likely to revise the engine mapping and possibly the camshaft profile to unlock more top-end power and torque.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Expected Peak Power: </span>The current model offers <span class="font-weight-700">27.5 PS@6000 rpm. </span>The 2025 model is expected to be tuned for a peak power output closer to 30 PS, achieved at a slightly higher 6500 rpm. This increase is vital for highway performance and bragging rights.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Expected Peak Torque: </span>The torque (currently<span class="font-weight-700"> 36 Nm@4000 rpm) </span>might see a bump to 38 to 40 Nm, but more importantly, the peak torque curve will be broadened, meaning that maximum pulling power is maintained across a wider 3500 to 5500 rpm band. This enhanced flexibility is what riders on <span class="font-weight-700">BikeCarHub </span>look for in a mid-capacity machine.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Improved Cooling: </span>To handle the increased power, Hero might introduce minor, visible changes to the oil cooler, potentially increasing its surface area or optimizing airflow with the new body panels, ensuring thermal stability during prolonged high-speed cruising.</li>
                </ul>
                <p><span class="font-weight-700">Transmission and Mileage</span></p>
                <p>The Mavrick currently uses a 5-speed gearbox. A critical upgrade that is fiercely anticipated for 2025 is the introduction of a <span class="font-weight-700">6-speed transmission.</span></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">6-Speed Gearbox: </span>Adding a sixth gear would allow the rider to sit at high speeds (e.g., 100 km/h to 120 km/h) at lower engine RPMs. This would drastically improve <span class="font-weight-700">refinement, reduce engine noise, and increase long-distance riding comfort.</span></li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Slipper and Assist Clutch: </span>While the current Mavrick has an Assist clutch, the 2025 model may feature a more refined<span class="font-weight-700"> Slipper and Assist Clutch (SAC) </span>for even lighter clutch pull and better stability during rapid downshifts—a must-have for a performance roadster.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>The expected mileage will remain highly competitive, likely hovering around 32 to 35 km/l, offering a practical blend of performance and economy.</p>
                <h3 class="subheading">Running Gear and Dynamics: Stepping up the Handling Game</h3>
